item.title: Sample Page
item.dc:creator: richard
item.content:encoded:
This is an example page. It's different from a blog post because it will stay in one place and will show up in your site navigation (in most themes). Most people start with an About page that introduces them to potential site visitors. It might say something like this:
Hi there! I'm a bike messenger by day, aspiring actor by night, and this is my blog. I live in Los Angeles, have a great dog named Jack, and I like piña coladas. (And gettin' caught in the rain.)
...or something like this:
The XYZ Doohickey Company was founded in 1971, and has been providing quality doohickeys to the public ever since. Located in Gotham City, XYZ employs over 2,000 people and does all kinds of awesome things for the Gotham community.
As a new WordPress user, you should go to your dashboard to delete this page and create new pages for your content. Have fun!

item.title: FreeSpirit ESU Summer Camp 2015
item.dc:creator: buff
item.content:encoded: Hello. This is the blog site for our daily dose of Summer Camp. We will be updating this blog every day, with stories, photos and mad experiences! Please come back often and interact with us by leaving comments!

wp:comment.wp:comment_content: Of course we will now expect Rhodri to continue the cooking when he gets home!! No excuses now we have photographic evidence!

item.title: And we're Off!
item.dc:creator: buff
item.content:encoded: A stunningly lovely day welcomed the intrepid Explorers from FreeSpirit as we embarked upon our trusty steed (St Albans School mini-bus) and headed for Penycae, North Wales. The "fun-bus" headed up through Mid Wales to our lunch stop at Craven Arms. A diversion, due to a major accident, didn't deter us...and we were pulling into the car park of 1st Penycae Scout Group around 3.40pm. Gerry, the local Group Scout Leader, kindly welcomed us to his scout hut, turned the hot water on...and gave us directions to the local Tesco's. A lovely scout hut; plenty of room; nice showers...and a very good kitchen. One successful shop later (I don't think the local population...or our Explorers were more supprised to see a bunch of blokes running around the store and generally getting in everyones way!). Preperation for dinner...home-made pitza's, followed by a campfire awaits! Rhys (aka Bombsquad) and Euan...hard at work readying our woodpile for later! Whilst "kitchen managers" Rob and Jack are working hard on our dinner...Senior Dinner Manager (Lewis) looks on!

wp:comment.wp:comment_content: Looks like you're having fun already.......Glad to hear the showers are nice.....no excuse for smelly scout 'pits' amongst other things!!!......especially you Euan. Have a fab week all. Hope the weather stays good.
Thanks Heather...we always run a "minger free camp"!

Obviously no spellchecker on your blog, Si!
Looks lovely. Enjoy yourselves!

item.title: Breakfast n lunch...
item.dc:creator: buff
item.content:encoded: At FreeSpirit, we are very health conscious and eat accordingly. Therefore, an extremely healthy "big boy" breakfast was consumed by all (after our 5 mile morning run!)...3 sausages, 3 bacon, eggy bread, mushrooms, black pudding, baked beans. Packed lunch underway by Lewis and Rod...and we're off out.

wp:comment.wp:comment_content: Amazing to see Lewis up and put to work before lunchtime!!! Hope he has remembered to spray pits #BO!!!

My baby boy Euan has learned to cook with his mummy.....so glad he's able to show off his culinary skills and help cook for you all. Make sure you don't poison anyone though Euan.....or gas them with your stinky pits or smelly arse!!! Remember son, mummy always loves you and misses you xxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxx
A ha ha ha - awesome! :)
He has till midnight- bulldozer standing by. In fairness how he slept through last nights racket was amazing.... He didn't want to move this morning. In/out sleeping bag lol!

item.title: Llangollen...and "comments"
item.dc:creator: buff
item.content:encoded: A fairly wet day today...but not detered, we headed over to Llangollen. A wander around the town, a coffee, and a stroll along the river Dee. We've headed back to our excelent hut...and have resumed "extreme Monopoly"...Rob style! PS...we are lurvin' the "comments"...Heather in pole at this time!!!

item.title: Wow! It's still raining....
item.dc:creator: rhys
item.content:encoded:
Ok I admit it..... The Explorers seem to be coping with the rainy day better than the leaders!
The amount of today's rain is actually greater than the magnitude of Lewis' new airbed ( which is colossal ).
Ewan is getting embarrassed. Rhodri is making so much noise in the kitchen it's unreal. Rob and Jack are like a double comedy act. Simon is geeking the Tour de France..... And Mike is ruling the kitchen.
Me, I'm off to get Alex from Telford later, I'm contemplating taking a speedboat instead of the minibus..
STOP BLEEDING RAINING!!!!!

wp:comment.wp:comment_content: Yeah been raining here all day too, but we have used the time usefully to de-fumigate Lewis' bedroom, including removing large quantities of bogies etc.#GROSS

The rain has been torrential here today too. Don't fret my little man, if its that bad all week, you'll still be able to get home for huggles with mummy by lying on your airbed and putting your ginormous feet to good use as flippers! Mummy loves and misses you as always xxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxx

item.title: King of the Titan!
item.dc:creator: buff
item.content:encoded: What a day! Titan Zip-wire followed by Bounce-Below... It all started with a trip over to Blaenau Ffestiniog which was about an hour and a half in the mini-bus. We then got kitted up by the brilliant staff at Titan...and so the adventure began... Run 1 - about 1 KM...a good speed. Run 2 - less distance...but the fastest run. Run 3 - straight from the mountain to our car-park! ...what amazing fun...I want to do it again. We had borrowed a "Go-Pro" camera...and managed to get some reasonable video (which will be uploaded when we return) Enjoy...! Zip3_Run2

item.title: A magical Bounce Below...and a river!
item.dc:creator: buff
item.content:encoded: Bounce Below is a series of old slate caverns that have ropes, nets, trampolines, walk-ways, and shoots, on different levels...all designed to allow us to safely run wild and bounce about. This was our main activity for the afternoon. It was immense fun...and very tiring. [caption id="attachment_91" align="alignnone" width="300"] DCIM100GOPRO[/caption] ....more photos coming soon. On our way home, we popped into Betws-y-Coed for a wander around the shops and explore the river...before succumbing to an awesome lasagne back at our camp.

wp:comment.wp:comment_content: Well I see you are all modelling the latest fashion in shoe wear! Not sure that will catch on here- far too wet!! Looks like great fun. Must challenge Rhodri to a repeat performance- I love zip slides. Tell him to smile next time you take a photo- go on Rhodri- you can actually smile you know! Very quiet without him. We had to do our own washing up but we can leave the rest of the weeks washing up for him to do when he gets back!!!

Looks like you've had a phenomenal day. Would have loved being there to watch you all enjoying the zip wire and cave trampolines.......I bet all the little soldiers are tired - sleep tight now little men as you'll probably have a busy and tiring day tomorrow!!!!

item.title: Food glorious food....
item.dc:creator: Explorers
item.content:encoded: Junior master chef needs to look out....we have some budding kitchen guru's ....it all started sat evening.....Pizza for tea.great says the lads..Domnios? Hell no way......your making your own. From the dough base up....there was flour everywhere..but a production line preparing the toppings was soon underway..all the lads can now cook pizza...Sunday tea saw half a pig slow roasted with all the trimmings...oh the joys of having an oven to use.....Monday.....after a zipping n bouncing day rob n jack...or jack n Jill as the others now call them took up the baton to make home made lasagne...aided by rod n Alex on veg prep...spicy wedges n lasagne. (Rob n jack have worked out that if they cook they don't have to wash up) ....but we have discovered that Ewan apart from stinking everyone out loves to wash up...MUM take note......tomorrow. The kitchen will be loaned to bomb squad....and if he does a good job I'll let him do it again.......it's now 11 20 n the lads have demolished the cheese board n tubs of home made pop corn and are all looking a) bloated b) very tired but happy.......Osama bin cooking...( mike)

wp:comment.wp:comment_content: Glad to know Euan likes to wash up.....Will make sure that's his job when we go on holiday this year......you will need to try and get him to wash his stinky pits as well as he washes dishes now......before he comes home this week if possible please!!! Still love and miss you my little baby boy xxxxxxx :)

item.title: Snowdon... at the summit
item.dc:creator: buff
item.content:encoded: Having spent the last 2-3hours in rain as we headed up Snowdon, singing all the way, we felt that we had earned a warm break in the Snowdon Cafe having a well earned lunch...

item.title: Waterworld...and Bowling
item.dc:creator: buff
item.content:encoded: Today was supposed to be a warm, sunny beach day...and so we headed off for Waterworld, which is in Wrexham. The intrepid FreeSpirits hit the water and a number of appropriate challenges then took place - The pool complex contained a "wild-water" river with a small waterfall. Rapid circuits began with us all becoming submerged when swimming under the waterfall...the first challenge was to legibly shout "wassuppp"! However, the main competition was to achieve the most 360 degree spins whilst hurtling down the water slide...Rob started us off with 10; Buff clocked in at 17; Euan crept in at 17...then superman Lewis achieved 24! Not to be out done, Euan went back and managed to squeeze in one last run...achieving a fantastic gold medal run of 25! ...simply stunning! Following a three course lunch which included a good sized steak, we headed over to "Tenpin" for a swift 10 pin bowl. We split into 2 lanes...Lewis, Euan, Jack, Rhys, Rob were on one team...with Euan again pole with a good win. Mike, Buff, Alex and Rod were on the other lane. Mike moved into an early lead...but Rod came back strongly and narrowly missed taking the game! A wander through Wrexham, whilst heading towards our trusty mini-bus, found their cathedral...building of the day award!

wp:comment.wp:comment_content: Well done on the bowling Rhodri! Glad you liked the pool in Wrexham- it didn't look like that when I went swimming with school there! Mind you that was just a few years ago - not going to tell you how many although I did live near Llangollen for over 20 years. Nice to see St. Giles again, it is a beautiful church. That's the cultural tour done, now get on with the fun!!! Have you started a 'who can make naughty bits out of food' competition? Please don't let anyone buy Chelsea buns, I dread to think of those pictures!!!

item.title: What am I doing with my life😂
item.dc:creator: Explorers
item.content:encoded: Just climbed all the way to the top of snowdon (well done boys) to find a rather large lake, jokingly I said to Mike "can I go skinny dipping", Mike replied to my surprise "if u keep your boxers on", we both laughed. On the way down we were all very tired, so we decided to walk on the path because it was easier on our feet. It just so happens that the path was along side the lake, I decided to jump in😂, the water must have been 0.1 degrees from freezing temperature because I thought I was gonna die😭, so now you know the life of a Jack😂😂😂

item.title: Today's Challenge...Snowdon
item.dc:creator: buff
item.content:encoded: After an early start (6.30am), bacon butties, sausage butties and a good hour or so driving...we were ready to start our day's walk up Snowdon. It was cool, cloudy but sunny intervals...for about 10 minutes! As we headed up the Pig Track...seriously dark clouds were gathering...and then the heavens opened. It rained pretty much on and off for the next 2-3 hours as we headed for the summit. The mist and cloud layer was lying all over the big peaks. However, as we dropped onto the ridge just below the summit, the wind now hit us....absolutely freezing! We moved up the last few hundred meters...and headed straight into the cafe!

wp:comment.wp:comment_content: For heavens sake Rhodri try smiling on a photo!!! Shame it was poor weather, it's a lovely hike in the warm. Bet you'll all be aching tomorrow!

item.title: Heading down
item.dc:creator: buff
item.content:encoded: As we left the cafe, the temperature had dropped even further, the wind had increased and it was still raining! Mike stated that previous walks in the middle of winter were not as cold! We therefore spent but a few seconds on the trig point for the obligatory photo, before heading down the Miners Track for another team photo...seagull photo...and, Jack and his chicken on the summit We were out of the wind, the rain had temporally stopped and we were heading down for the lake. There then followed a swimming challenge!

item.title: The final hour
item.dc:creator: buff
item.content:encoded: The rain had stopped for a while now and the Miners Track was easy on the boot. We made good time, arriving at the bus around 4pm...a great day's walking with a brilliant bunch of people! And, just to rub salt into the wound...it is gloriously sunny back at camp!

wp:comment.wp:comment_content: What a fantastic achievement.....Looks like you had a fab day despite the rain.....Love all the photos. Well done everyone. I'm sure it's something you'll remember for the rest of your lives. Not sure I would have fancied the swimming, or the near hypothermia as a result, but we'll done that brave man!!! You're all making us jealous back here.....wish we could join in with all your exciting exploits!!
Well done Guys on a great achievement today! You are certainly having some fab experiences up in North Wales. I'm sure you will all sleep well tonight!

item.title: Wassup Snowdon - Freespirit that's what! And they're steaming!
item.dc:creator: rhys
item.content:encoded:
Hello peeps! Bomb Squad here!
So today the intrepid Explorers of Freespirit and the Leaders hit Snowdon for a hike. After an eye watering 0630 wake up we demolished sausage and bacon sarnies and embarked on the fun bus for Pen Y Pass.
This is where it really started to get interesting...
XC Weather, Met Office you little liars!
Anyway suffice to say it chucked it down, I'm not exactly sure how we angered Zues but he had the last laugh...
So we ascended the Pyg Path to the summit in about 3 hours. The Explorers we amazing, actually considering the weather they were exceptional.
You learn so much more when the weather is a challenge hillwalking.
After getting to the summit rather refreshed by the wind and rain we took shelter in the Train Station Cafe'. The guys demolished their packed lunches with all the restraint of Predator!
Thinking the weather might improve, we trekked to the summit for a Team Photo, might as well be a steam photo ( we were giving off enough of it! ).
We returned to Pen Y Pass, via a rather slippery miners track. Ewan called the slips as they occurred, emerging from the mountain like a steaming warrior Jack threw himself in the lake, full dunk, he got out 12 times faster than he went in...
Hero!
We returned this eve full of team spirit, laughing at the weather and the mountain of wet kit. And thats the way it should be!
;-)

item.title: Tree-Top Challenge
item.dc:creator: buff
item.content:encoded: Today we woke to a sunny sky! How fickle can the weather be!!!! Into the bus and back to Betws y Coed to Tree Top Adventure...Following a detailed safety briefing and kit check, we were led up into the trees and set off on our first tree-top challenge - the orientation ring. This was a series of challenges involving moving from one tree to the next (normally 5-10 meters away). The method of crossing could be wobbly planks, a single rope, old tyres, of a Tarzan swing. At this point we were only 6-8 feet from the ground. Once we had all survived the "orientation ring" we went on to similar challenges...but we were now 40 feet up! The final challenge was a 50 feet straight drop on a "fan decender"...a serious test of belief in ones safety kit...little did we know that this was a mere baby compared to our next challenge...more of that later, enjoy the photos. item.title: Fan Decender...of death!
item.dc:creator: buff
item.content:encoded: Following our intrepid tree-top challenges, we headed for the largest tree in the forest and a test of fitness (to reach the tree-top platform) and a massive test in believing in oneself (and the safety kit!). The climb up this tree took 5-10 minutes. Once at the top, we clipped into the safety line before moving to the "launch" point. Here we were attached to the fan decender line...and then it was time to fly! One, two, three...step off... Enjoy!!

item.title: 3G Swing...and chillout
item.dc:creator: buff
item.content:encoded: The final challenge of the day was the multi-person 3G-Swing. This involved being clipped onto a big steel girder...gently lifted backwards and up to the top of the tree line. Then... One, two, three...pull the release.......... And you were catapulted through the air towards the ground and then off over the centre buildings...before swinging back again...fantastic! ...and then home again for tea (chicken curry) and a chill.

wp:comment.wp:comment_content: Phenomenal day again for you all......such fun!!!! Wish we were there too.....enjoy. :)

item.title: Full Moon...fresh bread...and hammocks
item.dc:creator: buff
item.content:encoded: Another great evening. Following our excellent curry, the unit all setup their hammocks in the nearby wood.   This was immediately followed by Mike reallocating the Moon (hopefully you were not inconvenienced by the odd tsunami)! The evening late film couldn't finish soon enough and then a first night in hammocks for many commenced. One conversation, overheard "loving my hammock, but can someone please turn out the big light... ...the "big light".

item.title: Historical Chester....and 1000 paintballs!
item.dc:creator: buff
item.content:encoded: Our last full day has arrived! After our usual "big boy" breakfast (sausages, bacon, mushrooms, black pudding, baked beans etc) we piled into our trusty mini bus and headed off for Chester. The morning was free time - wandering around this lovely historical city. Mike found the shop that was appropiate to his age! But the real reason for coming to Chester (and the main event) was to spend the afternoon paintballing! Five different scenarios (Lego, tyres, church, missile attack, Hamburger Hill) - 10 games in all. The Unit was split into 2 teams to partake in our "Call of Duty" fantasy's, which saw plenty of camping, no-scoping and shouts of "man down, man down"....and no mater how many times we asked, we never did get a "Huey Medivac"! Five hours of combat later, we dragged our battered and bruised bodies back to the "APC" and took "red route 1" back to our fire-base - aka, Penycae.....more on bruises later!

wp:comment.wp:comment_content: Wow! Amaze-balls!!! You have all done so much in one week, one to remember I'm sure! Thank you for giving the boys the opportunity to do things they would probably not have the courage to do normally. Certainly the true spirit of scouting. And now I can't wait to take Rhodri back to do them again- I thought I was the only dare devil in the family!

item.title: Flaming Pillars of death...and a few bruises!
item.dc:creator: buff
item.content:encoded: Following an amazing chilli, we headed outside to end the camp by launching a few Chinese lanterns...(for those of you in the know, they were the last from the infamous "Youlbury" vintage...say no more!). As dusk was deepening and working in teams of three we managed to launch a number of lanterns over the nearby fields...before heading inside for the "bruise" competition and our final film night. The "bruise" competition: As you have probably guessed, this was the post paintballing "who's got the most bruises". There were two titles up for grabs -1. the person with the most bruises (Won by Mike), and 2. the most amazing bruise (Won by Euan with a collarbone special!)...enjoy
